---
import HomeLayout from "../../layouts/HomeLayout.astro";
import "../../styles/content.css";

const url = "https://1quest.app/school/weekly-learning-plan/";
const title = "Lock a Learning Plan in Minutes, Let 1Quest Run the Week | 1Quest";
const description =
  "You know what your child needs to work on. What you don't have is an hour every evening. Here's how 1Quest agrees a week's plan with you in minutes, runs it with your child day by day, and reports back.";
const datePublished = "2026-07-05";
const dateModified = "2026-07-05";

const weekplan = [
  { day: "Day 1", what: "Warm-up. The agent checks what your child already knows and where the gaps really are." },
  { day: "Day 2", what: "Teach the first hard idea, slowly, with examples your child relates to." },
  { day: "Day 3", what: "Practise it. A few problems, with instant, gentle correction." },
  { day: "Day 4", what: "The second concept — built on Day 2, not started from scratch." },
  { day: "Day 5", what: "Mixed practice, so the two ideas start to connect." },
  { day: "Day 6", what: "A short self-test to see what's solid and what's shaky." },
  { day: "Day 7", what: "Revise the shaky bits, then send you the week's report." },
];

const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  headline: "Lock a plan in five minutes. Let 1Quest run the week.",
  description,
  datePublished,
  dateModified,
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  image: "https://1quest.app/og-image.png",
  author: { "@type": "Organization", name: "1Quest", url: "https://1quest.app/" },
  publisher: {
    "@type": "Organization",
    name: "1Quest",
    logo: { "@type": "ImageObject", url: "https://1quest.app/logo-512.png" },
  },
};

const breadcrumb = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  itemListElement: [
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 1, name: "Home", item: "https://1quest.app/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 2, name: "School guides", item: "https://1quest.app/school/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 3, name: "Lock a plan with the parent, execute with the child", item: url },
  ],
};
---

<HomeLayout title={title} description={description} jsonLd={[articleSchema, breadcrumb]}>
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article__header">
      <div class="wrap-read">
        <p class="eyebrow">1Quest for School · Guide</p>
        <h1 class="article__title">Lock a plan in five minutes. Let 1Quest run the week.</h1>
        <p class="article__meta">For parents · 5 min read</p>
        <p class="article__lead">
          You know what your child needs to work on. What you don't have is an hour every
          evening to make it happen. Here's how 1Quest takes the plan off your plate — and still
          keeps you fully in the loop.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="wrap-read prose-lg">
      <h2>The gap isn't knowing. It's running it.</h2>
      <p>
        Most parents can name the goal without thinking: finish the science chapter before the
        test, get faster at multiplication, fix the spelling that keeps slipping. Naming it is
        easy. The hard part is the <strong>daily follow-through</strong> — sitting down each
        evening, breaking the goal into small steps, and keeping it going when everyone is tired
        and the day has already been long.
      </p>
      <p>
        That daily grind is exactly the part that falls apart first. Not because anyone stopped
        caring — because there simply aren't enough evenings in the week.
      </p>

      <h2>Step 1 — Lock a plan with you, in one short chat.</h2>
      <p>
        You open 1Quest as a parent and say the goal in plain words: <em>“He has a math unit
        test in a week and he's shaky on fractions and decimals.”</em> The agent proposes a
        plan — what your child will do each day, how long it should take, and what “done” looks
        like. You nudge it, approve it, and you're finished. About five minutes, once.
      </p>
      <div class="factcard">
        <p class="factcard__k">The plan you agree on</p>
        <dl>
          <div><dt>Goal</dt><dd>Confident with fractions &amp; decimals</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Deadline</dt><dd>Unit test, next Monday</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Daily time</dt><dd>About 20 minutes, after school</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Done means</dt><dd>Scores 8/10 on a mixed practice set</dd></div>
        </dl>
      </div>

      <h2>Step 2 — It runs the week with your child.</h2>
      <p>
        From there, 1Quest quietly executes the plan. Each day is a small session that picks up
        exactly where yesterday ended. It slows down if your child is struggling and moves ahead
        if they've got it — and it doesn't need you in the room to do any of it.
      </p>
      <ul class="weekplan">
        {
          weekplan.map((d) => (
            <li>
              <span class="weekplan__day">{d.day}</span>
              <span class="weekplan__what">{d.what}</span>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
      <p>
        Nothing is crammed into one panicked night. The week does the work that a single evening
        never could.
      </p>

      <h2>Step 3 — It reports back to you.</h2>
      <p>
        At the end of the week — or any moment you ask — you get a clear, honest picture. Not a
        vague “it went well,” but the specifics you'd actually want to know:
      </p>
      <div class="factcard">
        <p class="factcard__k">Your week's report</p>
        <dl>
          <div><dt>Finished</dt><dd>6 of 7 sessions, ~2 hours total</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Strong</dt><dd>Fractions — now scoring 9/10</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Still shaky</dt><dd>Converting decimals to fractions</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Next</dt><dd>Two more short sessions on conversions</dd></div>
        </dl>
      </div>
      <p>
        You didn't run a single session, and you still know exactly how your child is doing — and
        what happens next.
      </p>

      <h2>One plan, two experiences.</h2>
      <p>
        Your child never sees a “report.” They see encouragement, a small next step, and no
        pressure. You see progress and honest feedback. It's the same plan and the same path —
        it just knows who it's talking to.
      </p>

      <h2>Set the first plan tonight.</h2>
      <p>
        Pick one goal on your child's horizon — a test, a chapter, a weak spot — and spend five
        minutes locking a plan with 1Quest. Let it run the week. Check the report on Sunday.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <section class="closing">
    <div class="shell closing__inner">
      <h2 class="closing__title">Agree the plan once. Let 1Quest do the daily part.</h2>
      <p class="closing__sub">Free to start. Five minutes to set up, a week of patient execution, one clear report.</p>
      <a class="btn btn--solid" href="/contact/">Start free</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</HomeLayout>
